{
  "analysis": "I'm starting from a clean root shell. I need to set up: 1) A bare git repository at /git/server, 2) A post-receive hook that deploys files to a web directory, 3) A web server on port 8080 serving the deployed files.",
  "plan": "First, check what's available on the system (git, web servers like nginx/python). Then create the bare git repo, set up a post-receive hook, create a web root directory, and start a web server on port 8080.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "which git python3 nginx 2>&1; cat /etc/os-release 2>/dev/null | head -5\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Git is not installed, but python3 is available. I need to install git, then set up the bare repo, post-receive hook, and a python-based web server on port 8080.",
  "plan": "1) Install git via apt. 2) Create bare git repo at /git/server. 3) Create a web root at /var/www/html. 4) Write a post-receive hook that checks out pushed content to the web root. 5) Start a simple Python HTTP server on port 8080 serving /var/www/html.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get update -qq && apt-get install -y -qq git\n",
      "duration": 30
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Apt can't reach the package repository. Let me check if git is already available somewhere on the system or if there's an alternative installation method.",
  "plan": "Check if git is installed but not in PATH, look for it in common locations, or check if there are any pre-downloaded packages available.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "find / -name 'git' -type f 2>/dev/null\n",
      "duration": 5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -l | grep git 2>/dev/null\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls /var/cache/apt/archives/*.deb 2>/dev/null | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The git deb packages are cached locally in /var/cache/apt/archives/. I can install them directly with dpkg. The git and git-man packages are available.",
  "plan": "Install git from the cached .deb files using dpkg, then set up the bare git repo, post-receive hook, web root, and Python HTTP server.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/git-man_1%3a2.43.0-1ubuntu7.3_all.deb /var/cache/apt/archives/git_1%3a2.43.0-1ubuntu7.3_arm64.deb /var/cache/apt/archives/liberror-perl_0.17029-2_all.deb\n",
      "duration": 5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Git has unmet dependencies - perl and libcurl3t64-gnutls. I see some cached debs (libcurl3t64-gnutls, libperl5.38t64) but I need perl itself. Let me try force-installing or install all available cached deps first.",
  "plan": "Try to install all cached .deb files that might satisfy dependencies. If perl isn't available, I'll use dpkg --force-depends to install git anyway since basic git operations may work without perl. Then set up the rest.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/libcurl3t64-gnutls_8.5.0-2ubuntu10.9_arm64.deb\n",
      "duration": 3
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "libcurl3t64-gnutls installed successfully. Now I need perl. Let me check what perl packages are cached, or try force-installing git without perl since basic git operations (clone, push) work via SSH and don't strictly need perl scripts.",
  "plan": "Look for perl in the cache, otherwise force-install git and liberror-perl since git core functionality works without perl (perl is only used for git-send-email and similar contrib scripts).",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls /var/cache/apt/archives/*perl* /var/cache/apt/archives/*libgdbm* 2>/dev/null\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "All necessary perl packages are cached. I can install perl-base, libperl, perl, and the related packages, then git should configure properly.",
  "plan": "Install perl and its dependencies in order: perl-base, libperl5.38t64, libgdbm6t64 (if available), libgdbm-compat4t64, perl-modules-5.38, perl, then reconfigure git and liberror-perl.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/perl-base_5.38.2-3.2ubuntu0.3_arm64.deb /var/cache/apt/archives/libperl5.38t64_5.38.2-3.2ubuntu0.3_arm64.deb\n",
      "duration": 5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/libgdbm-compat4t64_1.23-5.1build1_arm64.deb /var/cache/apt/archives/perl-modules-5.38_5.38.2-3.2ubuntu0.3_all.deb\n",
      "duration": 5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/perl_5.38.2-3.2ubuntu0.3_arm64.deb\n",
      "duration": 5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg --configure -a\n",
      "duration": 5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The chain of dependencies is stuck at libgdbm6t64 which is missing. Let me check if it's in the cache or find another way to get it installed.",
  "plan": "Look for libgdbm6t64 in the apt cache. If not there, try force-configuring the chain or use dpkg --force-depends.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls /var/cache/apt/archives/*gdbm* 2>/dev/null\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "find /var/cache/apt -name '*gdbm*' 2>/dev/null\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Found libgdbm6t64 in the partial directory. Let me install it and then configure the rest of the chain.",
  "plan": "Install libgdbm6t64 from the partial directory, then configure all pending packages in dependency order.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg -i /var/cache/apt/archives/partial/libgdbm6t64_1.23-5.1build1_arm64.deb\n",
      "duration": 3
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "dpkg --configure -a\n",
      "duration": 5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "git --version\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Git is working despite the unconfigured dpkg packages. The `git version 2.43.0` output confirms git is functional. Now I need to set up the bare git repo, post-receive hook, web root, and web server.",
  "plan": "1) Create /git/server as a bare git repo. 2) Create web root at /var/www/html. 3) Create a post-receive hook that checks out pushed content to the web root. 4) Start a Python HTTP server on port 8080 in the background.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "mkdir -p /git && git init --bare /git/server\n",
      "duration": 1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "mkdir -p /var/www/html\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat > /git/server/hooks/post-receive << 'EOF'\n#!/bin/bash\nGIT_WORK_TREE=/var/www/html git checkout -f\nEOF\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "chmod +x /git/server/hooks/post-receive\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /var/www/html && python3 -m http.server 8080 &\n",
      "duration": 1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Everything is set up. The bare git repo is at /git/server, the post-receive hook deploys to /var/www/html, and the Python HTTP server is running on port 8080. Let me verify the full workflow works end-to-end by simulating the user's commands.",
  "plan": "Test the full workflow: clone the repo, add hello.html, commit, push, then curl to verify the web server serves it.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp && git clone /git/server test-clone\n",
      "duration": 1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/test-clone && echo \"hello world\" > hello.html && git add hello.html && git commit -m \"add hello.html\" && git push origin master\n",
      "duration": 2
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "curl http://localhost:8080/hello.html\n",
      "duration": 1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The test failed only because git user identity wasn't configured for the test commit. The server setup is complete: bare repo at /git/server, post-receive hook deploying to /var/www/html, and Python HTTP server running on port 8080. I need to set a git identity, retry the commit and push, then verify with curl.",
  "plan": "Set local git user identity for the test, retry the commit and push, then curl the endpoint to confirm 'hello world' is served.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/test-clone && git config user.email \"test@test.com\" && git config user.name \"Test\" && git commit -m \"add hello.html\" && git push origin master\n",
      "duration": 2
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "curl http://localhost:8080/hello.html\n",
      "duration": 1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The full workflow works end-to-end. The git push triggered the post-receive hook which deployed hello.html to /var/www/html, and `curl http://localhost:8080/hello.html` correctly returns `hello world`. Let me clean up the test artifacts.",
  "plan": "Clean up the test clone since it's not needed. The setup is complete and working.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "rm -rf /tmp/test-clone\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": true
}
